jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!U8Ga!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40c05953-3cbb-4845-9a2f-cd7da8e68d96_736x899.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture></div></a><figcaption>by Alexis Carreiro on Pinterest</figcaption></figure></div><p>I am here trying to find my frontiers and in that, educating myself with what exists within the frontiers. It’s endless. It’s intimidatingly endless. I make it a goal everyday to do work that I enjoy, that I learn from and that brings me a little bit closer to finding my frontier. It is laborious work. It is delusional work. It is reaching your hand out in the dark, hoping you’ll find something wonderful because so far with every step you took you found something delightful.  It is believing that a creative idea exists in some corner of your brain, waiting to be extracted, unwound and rearranged to make sense of something you haven’t understood yet.</p><p> I wonder if it will ever be. If my purpose will ever be realised. But the thing with life is,  to make choices that bring you closer to the kind of person you want to be. And I want to be a free person. I want to freely express, help others express themselves and come back home to more curiosity, more care and more creative restlessness.</p><p>Six months back, my week was forty hours of nine to five, waiting for the weekend to feel better about myself. I was doing important work but it was not the least bit important to me. Today, I wake up with an empty slate. My day starts with words, I journal. Followed by more words, I write. I am building my writing muscle. Right now it’s 10.30 am on Monday morning and I am writing this. By afternoon, I’m editing the performance set for my debut show in February 2026—a deadline that both terrifies and anchors me. And I will end the day reading things that inspire me to write.</p><p>Right now, I’m a 28-year-old who walked away from a consulting career, now in Mumbai, learning to live with less certainty and more curiosity.  In pursuit of understanding creativity and art, trying to build skill that is learnt and remembered, trying to create the illusion of familiarity with every part of the frontier as I discover it. I have decided I want to be a performing artist who writes feelings and recites what a rattled heart wants to hear in order to be comforted. </p><p>I am an artist because I care.</p></div></article></div><div><div id="discussion"><h4>Discussion about this post</h4></div><div><h3>Ready for more?</h3></div></div></div>
